The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation
		 Tuesday, July 20, 2004 				 Security council
																								New Delhi, July 19: The first meeting of the National Security Council today focused on streamlining the security set-up and ensuring better co-ordination between the council and the National Security Advisory Board, the team of experts from outside the government, reports our special correspondent.																								The NSC reviewed the national security council system. It also took stock of the security reforms process initiated in May 2001, said a press release issued after the two-hour meeting.																								The meeting was presided over by Prime Minister Manmohan Singh and attended by defence minister Pranab Mukherjee, home minister Shivraj Patil, NSC adviser J.. Dixit, chief of army staff .C. Vij and the governments interlocutor in Kashmir . Padmanabhaiah.																								After the Kargil war, then Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee asked a group of ministers headed by then home minister .K. Advani to review the working of the security system. The meeting decided to regularise and institutionalise meetings between the security experts and the council.																								The government recently reconstituted the security advisory board  a group of experts that assists the council and gives inputs on issues of strategic importance. Retired diplomat S.K. Lambah has been named the new convenor of the 15-member board, which has a two-year term.																								The Naga peace process was also reviewed at todays meeting. The negotiations with the Nationalist Socialist Council of Nagalim (Isak-Muivah) has come under strain following the United Progressive Alliances announcement that the northeastern boundaries of the state would not be reworked. The NSCN asserts that the only way to ensure a lasting solution to the problem is to bring all Naga inhabited areas under one geographical unit.
